    "label": "Anne Margaret Cooke Reid",
    "biographyMarkdown": "# Anne Margaret Cooke Reid \n## Received Ph.D. in Speech-Theater, 1944 \n\nAnne Margaret Cooke was born on October 6, 1907, to William Wilson Cooke and Anne M. Miller in Washington, D.C. Her father, William, was the first Black employee of the Office of the Supervising Architect. On her mother\u2019s side, her grandfather was Thomas Ezekiel Miller, a prominent educator and one of the only African Americans elected to Congress during the Jim Crow era. While she was a child, her family moved to Gary, Indiana where her father was the first African American to be a licensed architect. Anne attended high schools in Gary and later attended Oberlin College. She graduated from Oberlin in 1928 and taught English and speech at Spelman College. She took a year\u2019s leave in 1930 to study at the American Academy of Dramatic Arts.[^1] \n\nAt Spelman, she headed the Spelman Players, a student theatrical group. She also helped organize the University Players, which included Atlanta University, Morehouse College, and Spelman College. Building on her earlier collaboration among with Atlanta University, she helped establish the Atlanta University Summer Theater. The theater was the first Black summer theater in the country. She worked alongside Owen Dodson, another Black Yale graduate, in running the theater program.[^2] \n\nShe won a scholarship from the General Education Board that allowed her to attend Yale. She attended Yale School of Drama for a semester in the 1936-1937 school year where she studied methods of play production and acting. She later received a Rosenwald fellowship in 1938 that allowed her to pursue a Ph.D. at Yale. While at Yale, she served as a representative for the Association of American Colleges, lecturing around the country. After completing her residence requirements for the degree, Cooke took a position as director of the Communication Center at the Hampton Institute. She continued to run the Atlanta University Summer Theater while studying at Yale. For one of the plays in the summer, she directed the production of Elijah\u2019s Ravens which was a play done by Shirley Graham Du Bois, a fellow Black Yale student.[^3] \n\nShe received her doctorate degree in speech-theater from Yale in 1944. For her dissertation, Cooke wrote on the acting styles of English actors in the eighteenth century. Cooke left Hampton, and with Owen Dodson, taught at Howard University. At Howard, Anne served as the director of dramatics. Together, Cooke and Dodson ran the Howard Players and received acclaim across the world. In 1949, the U.S. Department of State sponsored Cooke and the Howard Players\u2019 tour across Scandinavia for cultural diplomacy. While at Howard, she received a Fulbright award to study theater in Norway at the University of Oslo in 1951.[^4] \n\nIn 1958, she married Ira De Augustine Reid, a prominent Black sociologist and professor at Haverford College. Around the time of her marriage, she left Howard and taught at Haverford and Bryn Mawr in Pennsylvania. After the death of her husband in 1968, she worked at the University of California at Santa Cruz as a senior preceptor and an associate professor. By the 1970s, she taught at the University of Maryland. She was recognized as the \u201cFirst Lady of Black Theatre\u201d and received the Outstanding Pioneer Award by AUDELCO which recognized her contributions to Black theater. Some of her students included Shauneille Perry, Roxie Roker, Joseph Walker, Zaida Coles, Graham Brown, Ted Shine, Ellis Haizlip, and Toni Morrison.[^5] \n\nShe retired in 1985, moving to Washington, D.C., and later White Plains, New York. She died on February 13, 1997.[^6] \n\nImage citation: Spelman College Photographs Collection, Spelman College Archives.\n\n[^1]:\u201cPioneering Black Architect William Wilson Cooke,\u201d U.S. General Services Administration Blog, https://www.gsa.gov/blog/2021/02/24/pioneering-black-architect-william-wilson-cooke; https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/279007920/anna-margaret-reid; \u201cHon T. E. Miller, Last S.C. Race Congressman, Grandfather of Miss Anne M. Cooke, Passes Away,\u201d *Atlanta Daily World*, April 13, 1938, 1; Leslye Joy Allen, \u201cThe birth of Queen Anne: Re-discovering Anne M. Cooke at Spelman College,\u201d in The *Routledge Companion to African American Theatre and Performance* (London: Routledge, 2018), 134-135; Bernard L. Peterson, *Profiles of African American Stage Performers and Theatre People, 1816-1960*, (New York: Greenwood Press, 2001), 86. \n\n[^2]:\u201cSummer Theater to Open at Atlanta University for Sixth Year June 30: Five Productions to Be Staged by Actors During Five-Week Period; Mystery Play Opening Performance,\u201d *The Call*, June 23, 1939, 17; \u201cAtlanta U. To Continue Summer School Theater,\u201d *The Call*, May 31, 1940, 15.  \n\n[^3]:\u201cHigher Degrees Sought by Atlanta U. Teacher,\u201d *The Call*, September 25, 1936, 8; \u201cAnne M. Cooke, Of Spelman Staff, Lecturing at Mid-West Colleges,\u201d Atlanta Daily World, March 3, 1941, 1; \u201cAnne Cooke Becomes Communications Head at Hampton Institute,\u201d *The New York Age*, August 21, 1943, 4; \u201cAtlanta U. Presents Shirley Graham Play,\u201d *New York Amsterdam Star-News*, July 12, 1941, 21.  \n\n[^4]:\u201cHoward U. Offers \u2018All My Sons\u2019 First Time in D.C.,\u201d The Washington Post, February 5, 1948, 8; \u201cMrs. Roosevelt Bids Bon Voyage to Howard U. Players,\u201d New York Herald Tribune, September 1, 1949, 9; \u201c21 Negro Students to Act in Norway: Howard U. Troupe Will Start Series of Ibsen Offerings at Oslo in September,\u201d *The New York Times*, July 28, 1949; \u201cThree Chosen to Study Overseas,\u201d *Atlanta Daily World*, September 11, 1951, 2.  \n\n[^5]:\u201cDr. Reid of Haverford Marries Howard Prof,\u201d *Philadelphia Tribune*, August 23, 1958, 14; \u201cYale PhD Enhances UC Santa Cruz Campus,\u201d *Oakland Post*, February 18, 1971, 14; \u201cAudelco honoring First Lady of Black Theatre, Nov. 18,\u201d *New York Amsterdam News*, November 16, 1974, B10; \u201cThe Audelco winners,\u201d *New York Amsterdam News*, November 30, 1974, D14. \n\n[^6]:*The Daily Item*, February 15, 1997, 6. \n\n \n",
    "description": "Received Ph.D. in Speech-Theater, 1944",
    "publicationsMarkdown": "\"Tribal Distribution in the Great Basin,\" *American Anthropologist* 40, no. 4 (1938).\n\n\u201cThe Atlanta University Summer Theatre,\u201d *The Crisis* 19, no. 11 (1941).  \n\n\"Eighteenth Century Acting Styles,\" *Phylon* 5, no. 3 (1944).\n\n\"The Little Theatre Movement as an Adult Education Project Among Negroes,\" *The Journal of Negro Education* 14, no. 3 (1945).\n\n\"Review of *The Quarry*,\" *The Journal of Negro Education* 17, no. 2 (1948).\n\n\"Review of *The Beast of the Haitian Hills*,\" *The Journal of Negro Education* 17, no. 4 (1948).\n\n\"The Wild Duck Comes Home,\" *The Record* 6, no. 2 (1950).\n\n\"An Analysis of the Acting Stlyes of Garrick, Siddons, and Edmund Kean in Relation to the Dominant Trends in Art and Literature of the Eighteenth Century.\" PhD diss., Yale University, 1944.\n",
